🌿 Are These Two Statements Contradictory?
Or Are They Revealing the Same Non-dual Truth?
While reflecting on Yoga Vāsiṣṭha – Brahma Gītā – Aindava Upākhyāna (Sarga 178, Part 4), two revered seekers offered profound observations:
Swami Ashokanand Ji writes:
"निराकार में समस्त आकार और सब आकारों में निराकार विद्यमान है। जैसे जल में समस्त लहरें और समस्त लहरों में केवल जल ही विद्यमान है।"
Dr. Ratan Lal Sharma Ji writes:
"साकार में निराकार ब्रह्म स्थित है और उसी ऊर्जा से समस्त कार्य संचालित हो रहे हैं।"
At first sight, one appears to begin with the Formless, the other with form.
Yet both are pointing toward the same indivisible Reality.
🌿 First Perspective — The Vision of Swami Ashokanand Ji
The emphasis is upon Brahman.
The Formless alone is Real.
All forms arise within It,
exist in It,
and dissolve back into It.
Like waves in the ocean,
no wave ever exists apart from water.
This is the standpoint of Paramārtha.
It echoes the declarations of the Upaniṣads:
"सर्वं खल्विदं ब्रह्म"
"All this indeed is Brahman."
and
"नेह नानास्ति किञ्चन"
"There is no multiplicity whatsoever."
🌿 Second Perspective — The Vision of Dr. Sharma Ji
The emphasis begins with the visible world.
Every form is animated by the invisible Brahman.
Without the unseen Reality,
no movement,
no life,
no thought,
no universe could exist.
This beautifully recalls the Bhagavad Gītā:
"मया ततमिदं सर्वं जगदव्यक्तमूर्तिना" (9.4)
"This entire universe is pervaded by Me in My unmanifest form."
Here the teaching begins with the world and leads us back to its unseen foundation.
🌿 Yoga Vāsiṣṭha Unites Both
Mahārṣi Vasiṣṭha dissolves both viewpoints into one vision.
He teaches:
ऊर्म्यावर्तद्रवत्वादि शुद्धे जलघने यथा।
तथेदं सर्गपर्यायं ब्रह्मणि ब्रह्म भासते॥
Just as waves, whirlpools and currents are nothing but water,
this entire universe is Brahman appearing as Brahman.
He does not merely say:
"Brahman is inside the world."
Nor merely:
"The world is inside Brahman."
He reveals something subtler:
There are not two realities at all.
Only Brahman appears as all names and forms.
🌿 Living Vedanta Reflection
When we say:
"Form exists in the Formless,"
we speak from the side of Truth.
When we say:
"The Formless dwells in every form,"
we speak from the side of the seeker.
The destination is identical.
The river may begin from different banks,
yet it reaches the same ocean.
🌺 Take Away
The enlightened do not argue whether Brahman is in the world,
or the world is in Brahman.
They see that both expressions are compassionate pointers.
When knowledge matures,
both statements dissolve into one silent realization:
There is only Brahman.
The Formless appears as every form,
yet never ceases to be Formless.
🕉️ "ब्रह्म सत्यं। जगन्मिथ्या। जीवो ब्रह्मैव नापरः।"
"Brahman alone is Real. The world is Its appearance. The individual Self is none other than Brahman."
